d": 1252}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CDKN1b and CDKN1c genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5887005925178528, "span": {"begin": 1264, "end": 1287}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1027"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CDKN1b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9965482354164124, "span": {"begin": 1264, "end": 1270}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1028"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CDKN1c genes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9920080900192261, "span": {"begin": 1275, "end": 1287}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.5349470376968384, "span": {"begin": 1371, "end": 1376}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA gene structure", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6166220307350159, "span": {"begin": 1465, "end": 1485}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "promoter regions", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8690032958984375, "span": {"begin": 1525, "end": 1541}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8167269229888916, "span": {"begin": 1545, "end": 1556}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.5423204898834229, "span": {"begin": 1662, "end": 1667}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9970085024833679, "span": {"begin": 1680, "end": 1683}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.46697545051574707, "span": {"begin": 1694, "end": 1699}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "miRNA transcripts", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.8551458716392517, "span": {"begin": 1779, "end": 1796}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9987894892692566, "span": {"begin": 1833, "end": 1836}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DDR&#", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.5812069177627563, "span": {"begin": 1853, "end": 1858}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:780"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "DDR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.6523662209510803, "span": {"begin": 1853, "end": 1856}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968975782394409, "span": {"begin": 1896, "end": 1899}}], "text": "Various transcription factors regulate miRNA expression.The p53 protein also functions as a transcriptional repressor by binding to miRNA promoters and preventing the recruitment of transcriptional activators.For example, p53 prevents the TATA-binding protein from binding to the TAATA site in the promoter of the miR-17-92 cluster gene, suppressing transcription. Under hypoxic conditions, the miR-17-92 cluster is suppressed by a p53-dependent mechanism, making cells more susceptible to hypoxia-induced death (Yan et al.,2009). Cells can amplify the p53 signal by fine-tuning the p53 signalling pathway and the miRNA network, which improves cell sensitivity to external signals.  Other DNA damage-responsive transcription factors, such as NF-kB, E2F, and Myc, are also involved in miRNA &nbsp;transcription regulation. Both E2F and Myc promote miR-17-92 cluster transcription, which reduces E2F and Myc expression, establishing an autoregulatory negative feedback loop. Furthermore, Myc-induced miRNAs have an impact on cell proliferation and cell fate in Myc-mediated cells (Kim et al.,2010). Myc-induced miR-20a, for example, targets cdkn1a, a gene that encodes a negative regulator of cell-cycle progression, while Myc-induced miR-221 and miR-222 target the CDKN1b and CDKN1c genes, respectively, that trigger cell-cycle arrest. Little is currently known about how miRNA gene expression is transcriptionally regulated due to a lack of basic information about miRNA gene structure. Global prediction and verification of promoter regions of miRNA genes would allow us to further explore the functional interaction of transcriptional machinery and epigenetic miRNA regulation. p53 regulates miRNA maturation not only during transcription but also during processing of initial miRNA transcripts, resulting in crosstalk between the p53 network and the DDR&#39;s miRNA biogenesis machinery. Many p53-regulated miRNAs target proteins in the DDR, such as cell cycle progression and apoptosis, to affect the DDR.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:42:39 +0000 2026"}